The patient is a 52-year-old female with a past medical history significant for rheumatoid arthritis, atrial fibrillation, and reflux who presents today for her annual exam. She has been walking like she was told to do and exercising and doing yoga which has helped with her arthritis a lot. She has had no issues with joint pain in the last year but when she starts to get stressed, they start to flare up again. She does have some edema and some erythema on her methotrexate 2.5 mg once a week. For her atrial fibrillation, we would like to refer her to cardiology for a cardiac ablation which just maps out where it comes from and burns it so that it doesn't come back into normal sinus rhythm.

Reflux, reflux, GERD, gastroesophageal reflux disease (protonix) and allergies.

None

None

ASSESSMENT AND PLAN:
The patient has a history of rheumatoid arthritis, which is well controlled on methotrexate 2.5 mg once weekly. He also has atrial fibrillation, which is in and out of a-fib with a conversion pause followed by a return to sinus rhythm. For that reason, he is being referred to cardiology for cardiac ablation which maps out where that rhythm is coming from and burns it so that it does not come back. He continues on protonix 40 mg a day as well.
